When I came to Texas, Kunze had done quite a lot of 
characterization of the mineralogy of Texas

16:23.455 --> 16:34.764
soils. He's always done some more, but he had 
studied samples of the Houston Black, which is the

16:34.785 --> 16:50.157
state soil, and the Lufkin, which is a local soil, 
and the Beaumont, which is an acid soil they grow

16:34.785 --> 16:50.157
rice on. He had done the general mineralogy of 
them. reasonably well, and he was very

16:53.898 --> 16:57.504
methodical. He always had a good technician, and 
they did things very methodically, and so I had

16:57.605 --> 17:12.471
files of data, and have often gone back and pulled 
those out and compared, and that's been very

16:57.605 --> 17:12.471
effective. So I began to look for other things. The 
space era and the environmental eras have been

17:18.535 --> 17:28.028
factors that have influenced us. I had a student, 
David Carty, who came in as

17:28.969 --> 17:38.923
an undergraduate, and he wanted to do a a problem 
with library kind of study on how to contain a

17:39.359 --> 17:53.980
nuclear explosion out of a generating plant. Now, 
this is a long way back. We were still way back in the

17:55.422 --> 18:04.995
old State Chemist's Building, and a whole lot of 
things have happened in the country since then,

17:55.422 --> 18:04.995
and nobody had witnessed stuff. a nuclear event. 
And whenever we made contact, and David did this as

18:06.871 --> 18:24.363
his project, with a nuclear branch of government, 
they not only didn't want to share anything with

18:06.871 --> 18:24.363
him, they sort of scolded him for even asking the 
question. And he he had the idea that, well,

18:28.550 --> 18:45.830
someday there's going to be a meltdown and if we 
study the soils in the area, that we could make a

18:28.550 --> 18:45.830
berm around the site and we could contain whatever 
was there if we chose the soils correctly. And this

18:46.591 --> 18:54.220
would be a significant deterrent to the spreading 
of radioactive materials. As I say, he did what he

18:54.790 --> 18:59.477
could, but it was an unpopular topic. They didn't 
want to talk to him about it. But in the intervening

19:01.721 --> 19:06.468
years, we found out how prophetic his thoughts 
were. He was kind of a radical student, in a sense,

19:06.849 --> 19:10.494
talking about this sort of thing. But we know about 
Three Mile Island. We know about Chernobyl. And we

19:14.973 --> 19:19.638
know that that kind of information is really good 
thinking. And by the way, that young man is a

19:20.239 --> 19:24.684
consultant here in Bryan now. He works out of 
Bryan. So he's still pursuing environmental

19:27.707 --> 19:31.451
problems. So we did work. That was not a very 
in-depth endeavor, but that was one thing.

19:37.238 --> 19:43.765
Another one that comes to mind that's more novel 
