19:44.403 --> 19:52.011
worked as an undergraduate helping in the lab 
part-time, and he wanted to do some research. And

19:53.052 --> 20:10.630
it had happened there had been a young lady who was 
from the geography department, and she came in one

19:53.052 --> 20:10.630
day and she had about a dozen samples that she had 
picked up while she was touring near Pericatine

19:53.052 --> 20:10.630
Volcano in Mexico.

20:11.943 --> 20:14.608
She said, the crop's doing terrible there. These 
people can grow a good crop of corn. What's the

20:19.175 --> 20:19.977
problem? And she said, here are these samples. 
Well, you look at them and tell me about it. Well, I

20:25.566 --> 20:36.685
felt very humbled at that point because I didn't 
have any idea that I could do much looking at those

20:25.566 --> 20:36.685
samples to tell her why the corn didn't grow well in 
Pericotine. But she left them and she told me she

20:37.070 --> 20:41.237
would check back. And so I told this young man who 
was working with me, I said, now you want to do a

20:42.158 --> 21:00.748
piece of research, and we're doing soil 
mineralogy, would you take the clay out of those 12

20:42.158 --> 21:00.748
samples and we'll x-ray it and see what it is?

21:02.382 --> 21:02.843
He did. And we x-rayed them and it was the poorest 
set of x-ray patterns I think I ever saw. Out of the

21:09.351 --> 21:13.456
whole set we had two that had some small peaks on 
them. The others were just lines, just jiggle

21:13.476 --> 21:15.659
lines. Those days we had long strip charts. And 
that was, well, then came a student from

21:18.783 --> 21:28.355
oceanography, Tom McKee. And Tom really liked to 
work with electron microscopes. And that, he came

21:34.395 --> 21:39.043
to me because he thought I could use it for the 
electron mic work. And so he took those and looked

21:40.666 --> 21:55.710
at them, and that was before the, I believe it was 
the 10th

21:40.666 --> 21:55.710
International Soil Congress in Moscow. And Tom 
McKee looked at those little glass particles,

21:57.260 --> 22:08.400
which is mostly what those soils were, volcanic 
glass, and found little spots in them which we

22:08.752 --> 22:20.850
realized were hallucite, a particular kind of 
clay that forms in many soils and in volcanic soils

22:08.752 --> 22:20.850
particularly. And then we went to the other 
instruments, infrared and so on, and

22:20.870 --> 22:28.562
characterized what they were further. And I gave 
that paper in Moscow and it's published in the

22:29.683 --> 22:38.016
proceedings of that conference. From that, we had 
analyzed some soil from Guatemala. There's an

22:43.165 --> 23:02.080
aggie from Guatemala who used to come here every 
year because he had children in school here, and he

22:43.165 --> 23:02.080
would bring some samples with him, and he again 
would ask me questions like, I want to know if this

22:43.165 --> 23:02.080
will make good soil for growing tomatoes, which I 
wasn't exactly the person that should have been

23:02.684 --> 23:07.659
handling that kind of question. But he would also, 
in his position as an alumnus, he would leave me the

23:08.100 --> 23:15.883
samples and he'll say, all right, you send me the 
results. And Dr. Bloodworth, that's the only time

23:16.808 --> 23:26.278
that I can remember Dr. Bloodworth saying, would 
you like to meet this gentleman and help him out?

23:26.879 --> 23:28.100
And so and so I did. And we had found this one soil 
that had a lot of aloesite in it from Guatemala,

23:28.140 --> 23:38.372
volcanic soil. Well, some of it was spherical. And 
clays are making up of layers, and there's, if you

23:42.374 --> 23:51.545
distort a layer, it tends to roll and make a 
cylinder. And most all the holosite in the world

23:52.066 --> 23:58.293
that we knew about in those days was tubular. And 
here we found spheres. And so the clave scientists

24:02.298 --> 24:07.825
from all around wanted to know why spheres. In the 
glass from pericotine, we saw these spheres

24:08.918 --> 24:19.837
forming in bubbles at the microscopic level, at 
