24:19.857 --> 24:25.527
and that grew out of the undergraduate student's 
inquiry, the lady, the geography student

24:26.300 --> 24:41.345
bringing the sample from Mexico, and then I went 
later to the pericotine and sampled the soil again

24:26.300 --> 24:41.345
when I was in there. So that was, those were kind of 
isolated parts of research. But those were

24:46.754 --> 24:52.864
projects that you got involved in as a result of the 
student. Right. But what were your pet projects

24:53.545 --> 24:59.614
when you got here and how did they, what else, what 
did that lead to?

25:03.880 --> 25:13.975
Well, the history of clay mineralogy and soils for 
quite a long time was potassium chemistry. We all

25:15.254 --> 25:18.378
know that you've got nitrogen, phosphorus, and 
potassium. That's what the gardener puts on and

25:18.418 --> 25:22.083
makes fertilizer. So potassium, there's a lot of 
it applied. It's an expensive fertilizer

25:25.247 --> 25:28.912
amendment. And clays have potassium in the 
structure in some cases. And so we were always

25:35.881 --> 25:39.726
trying to figure out why some clays held why does 
the Houston black clay hold potassium

25:40.516 --> 25:45.834
effectively, or why it releases it? Well,

25:46.556 --> 25:53.479
that work was really the what we were pursuing 
whenever I mentioned Frank Hans earlier, that's

25:54.235 --> 26:01.225
the way that turned out up there. That the shortage 
of potassium was what they were trying to deal

26:01.826 --> 26:19.011
with, and the soil test would say they needed to 
apply soil potassium fertilizer, but the plant

26:01.826 --> 26:19.011
didn't respond that way. And in his work, we found 
that, well, there is enough mica in a certain

26:19.193 --> 26:30.027
fraction of that soil that it is releasing some 
potassium. And so that correlated with the

26:30.047 --> 26:34.173
available potassium to the plant. And we 
published that work. So that was one of my areas of

26:36.195 --> 26:45.127
interest, a subject much worked on by many soil 
scientists. What was next?

26:49.113 --> 26:53.721
Well, a lot of things that come to us in research are 
kind of coincidental. I was and am interested in

26:53.882 --> 27:10.952
iron oxides, and whenever I got to using the new 
microscope here, and growing out of Daryl

26:53.882 --> 27:10.952
Schultz's work to some degree, we had the tools to 
deal with iron oxides. And in this regional

27:11.422 --> 27:14.505
project, we want to deal with them. One of the basic 
problems with soils is that they may be chemically

27:14.525 --> 27:23.993
controlled reasonably well, but we cannot 
physically control them very well. And that is

27:24.614 --> 27:29.238
still a persistent problem, as we mentioned 
earlier. And so I wanted to analyze the iron oxides

27:30.079 --> 27:41.209
in some of the soils from the states and the 
regional group, as well as in Texas, and see what

27:41.662 --> 27:49.083
what there was about them that made the soil behave 
differently when we have quite a lot of iron oxide

27:41.662 --> 27:49.083
in them. The two major aggregating agents in soils 
are iron oxides and organic matter. being a

27:57.490 --> 28:00.294
mineralogist, I was looking at the iron oxide. 
After all, the red clays of Georgia are rather

28:00.314 --> 28:05.401
well-structured. And many of the red soils of the 
southeastern United States, they're rather

28:05.761 --> 28:10.688
well-structured. But the gray soils of Texas are 
not very well-structured. And so I began to look at

